abstract:
The multiattribute value function is a means of systematically analyzing preferences in the context of multiattribute or multicriteria decision making. We discuss in some detail the axiomatic foundations of the additive form of the multiattribute value function as an ordinal measure of preference, and the implications of these axioms for eliciting the parameters of the function. Extensions of the basic model to cardinal preference measures (generally implying nonadditive forms of the value function), and to application in mathematical programming problems (multiobjective optimization) are then discussed. We conclude with a brief discussion on the treatment of risk and of time values within the context of multiattribute value functions. 


Keywords: 

multiattribute decision making; 
multicriteria decision making; 
value measurement
